 global development support. Growing administrative pressures to document good care serve to preclude good care in practice while placing frontline healthcare workers in moral and ethical peril. Maternal health emergencies expose the precarity of hospital social relations and accountability systems, which, together, continue to lead to the deaths of pregnant women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMothersxMortalityxMoral and ethical aspectszTanzania. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520973916zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520973916zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520973916/original  a978-3-11-069041-5 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA